	<h3 class="title"><a href="/279813#comment-3049733" class="active">Besides - it's in the</a></h3>
    <div class="submitted active">Submitted by <a href="/user/40796" title="View user profile.">Blue Republic</a> on Mon, 04/22/2013 - 10:10.  <a class="permalink" href="/comment/3049733">Permalink</a></div>
	<div class="content">
     <p>self-interest of others to help those who have valuable<br />
practical skills - of which food production and processing/storing<br />
are pretty high up the list of useful things to be able to do.</p>
<p>If you can do this, not only are you better placed to help<br />
others, they have an incentive to help you.</p>
<p>I have grown wheat and barley before and given halfway<br />
decent conditions it is something that can be done with<br />
the most basic of tools and inputs - easier than a lot<br />
of vegetables. Most people don't know that, however<br />
since hardly anyone has ever tried (people that I know, anyway).</p>
<p>Now, I want to get to a higher level with my ability to process<br />
grains - next goal is malting grains! Wood fired oven would<br />
be good, too...</p>
<p>Knowing the basics of and having the basic infrastructure<br />
for food production, processing and storage is huge IMHO -<br />
think I need to acquire Smudge Pot's book.</p>
<p>Here's one I have acquired that Smudge and other preppers<br />
could probably appreciate:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Alaskan-Bootleggers-Bible-Leon-Kania/dp/0967452406" title="http://www.amazon.com/Alaskan-Bootleggers-Bible-Leon-Kania/dp/0967452406" rel="nofollow">http://www.amazon.com/Alaskan-Bootleggers-Bible-Leon-Kania/d...</a></p>
